JEREMY: So welcome everyone.

00:00:08.050 --> 00:00:11.160
Thanks for joining us today
for this very exciting Talks

00:00:11.160 --> 00:00:14.690
at Google with Kevin Kwan.

00:00:14.690 --> 00:00:16.980
So-- woo, yeah.

00:00:20.790 --> 00:00:23.400
My name is Jeremy, and I
lead the Asian Google network

00:00:23.400 --> 00:00:26.130
here at our Los Angeles office.

00:00:26.130 --> 00:00:28.890
We promote the professional
development and community

00:00:28.890 --> 00:00:32.009
involvement of our Googlers
and also bring you great events

00:00:32.009 --> 00:00:33.150
like this.

00:00:33.150 --> 00:00:35.994
So if you'd like to continue
seeing these events,

00:00:35.994 --> 00:00:37.410
please reach out
to me afterwards.

00:00:37.410 --> 00:00:38.910
We're always looking
for volunteers

00:00:38.910 --> 00:00:41.260
to help out with this.

00:00:41.260 --> 00:00:44.100
Just to tell you a
little bit about Kevin.

00:00:44.100 --> 00:00:47.550
Born in Singapore, Kevin Kwan
moved to the United States

00:00:47.550 --> 00:00:49.110
when he was 11.

00:00:49.110 --> 00:00:53.120
After graduating with degrees
from the University of Houston

00:00:53.120 --> 00:00:56.600
and Parsons School of
Design, Kevin worked for Andy

00:00:56.600 --> 00:01:00.910
Warhol's "Interview Magazine,"
"Martha Stewart Living,"

00:01:00.910 --> 00:01:02.540
and M&amp; magaz--

00:01:02.540 --> 00:01:06.050
company, the legendary
graphic design firm

00:01:06.050 --> 00:01:08.120
headed by Tibor Kalman.

00:01:08.120 --> 00:01:12.980
In 1999, Kevin establish his
own creative consulting firm

00:01:12.980 --> 00:01:15.470
where he became a highly
sought after producer

00:01:15.470 --> 00:01:18.350
of visual projects for
clients such as the New York

00:01:18.350 --> 00:01:25.280
Times, the Museum of Modern
Art, TED.com, and Oprah Winfrey.

00:01:25.280 --> 00:01:29.750
In 2013, Doubleday published
Kevin's first novel,

00:01:29.750 --> 00:01:32.510
"Crazy Rich Asians,"
which became

00:01:32.510 --> 00:01:34.700
an international
bestseller and has been

00:01:34.700 --> 00:01:37.850
translated into 13 languages.

00:01:37.850 --> 00:01:41.510
Its sequel, "China
Rich Girlfriend,"

00:01:41.510 --> 00:01:44.690
also rose to the top of the best
seller list around the world

00:01:44.690 --> 00:01:46.340
in 2015.

00:01:46.340 --> 00:01:49.840
And last week, the final
book in the trilogy,

00:01:49.840 --> 00:01:54.190
"Rich People Problems,"
debuted on the New York Times

00:01:54.190 --> 00:01:57.190
best seller list at number 12.

00:01:57.190 --> 00:01:58.930
Earlier this year,
Warner Brothers

00:01:58.930 --> 00:02:03.730
announced they had greenlit
"Crazy Rich Asians"

00:02:03.730 --> 00:02:06.310
and the movie is
now in production.

00:02:06.310 --> 00:02:09.580
Last month SCX
entertainment announce

00:02:09.580 --> 00:02:13.510
that it had acquired rights
to a new scripted drama series

00:02:13.510 --> 00:02:15.970
to be written by Kevin.

00:02:15.970 --> 00:02:18.350
Now please join me in
welcoming Kevin Kwan.

00:02:25.140 --> 00:02:29.791
KEVIN KWAN: See if this Coke
will slide off or be nice.

00:02:29.791 --> 00:02:31.290
Thanks so much for
being here today.

00:02:31.290 --> 00:02:33.123
I really appreciate
your taking the time out

00:02:33.123 --> 00:02:36.810
during your lunch to come
hear me say a few things.

00:02:36.810 --> 00:02:40.650
It's really a treat to
be here at Google Venice.

00:02:40.650 --> 00:02:43.650
Two years ago I had the honor of
speaking at Google headquarters

00:02:43.650 --> 00:02:47.310
in Mountain View and my mother
happened to be in the Bay Area

00:02:47.310 --> 00:02:48.660
at the time visiting a friend.

00:02:48.660 --> 00:02:51.120
So I thought, why don't
I invite her along

00:02:51.120 --> 00:02:52.860
to come check out Google?

00:02:52.860 --> 00:02:54.360
Right?

00:02:54.360 --> 00:02:56.610
My mom was at the
time, 76 years old.

00:02:56.610 --> 00:03:00.540
And she had just been recently
been given her first iPad ever.

00:03:00.540 --> 00:03:03.450
And her favorite thing
to do was go onto Google

00:03:03.450 --> 00:03:06.390
and look up all the extremely
rare and deadly types of cancer

00:03:06.390 --> 00:03:08.070
she thought she would get.

00:03:08.070 --> 00:03:10.170
So she was excited
to come to Google.

00:03:10.170 --> 00:03:13.320
And before I gave
my talk at Google,

00:03:13.320 --> 00:03:16.170
we were given a
tour of Google HQ.

00:03:16.170 --> 00:03:18.690
Lots of different departments
and divisions and really cool

00:03:18.690 --> 00:03:20.820
stuff that she
couldn't understand.

00:03:20.820 --> 00:03:24.480
And my mom is usually a very
talkative, social person,

00:03:24.480 --> 00:03:26.700
but she was pretty quiet
through the whole tour.

00:03:26.700 --> 00:03:29.970
And I just thought she
was bored out of her mind.

00:03:29.970 --> 00:03:34.050
Then we were taken to
the cafeteria for lunch--

00:03:34.050 --> 00:03:35.880
like the main
cafeteria, you know,

00:03:35.880 --> 00:03:37.740
where apparently
Larry and Sergey

00:03:37.740 --> 00:03:40.470
have a open house every Friday.

00:03:40.470 --> 00:03:42.870
And my mom's face lit up.

00:03:42.870 --> 00:03:45.780
I could see she was
impressed by the food,

00:03:45.780 --> 00:03:48.060
the amazing selections.

00:03:48.060 --> 00:03:50.520
And then when she found
out that food was free

00:03:50.520 --> 00:03:53.580
her eyes went huge.

00:03:53.580 --> 00:03:56.100
And you know, I think she went
to the Indian food station

00:03:56.100 --> 00:03:58.830
a couple of times and shoved
some naan into her handbag

00:03:58.830 --> 00:04:01.140
maybe.

00:04:01.140 --> 00:04:02.520
So after lunch I gave my talk.

00:04:02.520 --> 00:04:04.410
And then there was
a book signing.

00:04:04.410 --> 00:04:06.390
And as I sat at the
desk signing books

00:04:06.390 --> 00:04:09.090
for this long line of
people, I could see my mom

00:04:09.090 --> 00:04:12.600
going up and down the
line talking to people.

00:04:12.600 --> 00:04:14.790
And I was thinking,
what on earth

00:04:14.790 --> 00:04:16.050
could she possibly be doing?

00:04:16.050 --> 00:04:17.095
This is dangerous.

00:04:17.095 --> 00:04:17.970
You know what I mean?

00:04:17.970 --> 00:04:20.595
Like, is she trying to get some
secret Google code or something

00:04:20.595 --> 00:04:21.120
like that?

00:04:21.120 --> 00:04:23.790
Or find out more about cancer?

00:04:23.790 --> 00:04:26.850
And then as the line
shortened, I could hear her.

00:04:26.850 --> 00:04:31.350
And she was saying, to
everyone, excuse me,

00:04:31.350 --> 00:04:34.290
could you find my
son a job here?

00:04:34.290 --> 00:04:36.720
Are you guys hiring?

00:04:36.720 --> 00:04:38.010
Is there something he can do?

00:04:38.010 --> 00:04:39.120
My son is unemployed.

00:04:39.120 --> 00:04:42.450
He needs a job.

00:04:42.450 --> 00:04:46.200
So after we left
Google finally, she

00:04:46.200 --> 00:04:49.460
said to me in the car, ai-yah,
I wish you could get a job here.

00:04:49.460 --> 00:04:50.100
You'd be set.

00:04:50.100 --> 00:04:51.520
You'd have health insurance.

00:04:51.520 --> 00:04:53.310
You could use the
gym-- the amazing gym.

00:04:53.310 --> 00:04:54.630
You can swim.

00:04:54.630 --> 00:04:56.820
They have amazing curry.

00:04:56.820 --> 00:04:59.980
And I will finally,
finally be proud of you.

00:04:59.980 --> 00:05:01.450
So I think you guys--

00:05:01.450 --> 00:05:04.144
some of you here can relate.

00:05:04.144 --> 00:05:06.560
So some of you might know that
my first novel, "Crazy Rich

00:05:06.560 --> 00:05:09.780
Asians," is being made into
a movie by Warner Brothers.

00:05:09.780 --> 00:05:12.180
There's been a great deal
of talk and excitement

00:05:12.180 --> 00:05:15.180
because this is the first
romantic comedy ever

00:05:15.180 --> 00:05:18.660
in Hollywood history to
have an Asian male lead,

00:05:18.660 --> 00:05:22.350
an Asian heroine, and--

00:05:22.350 --> 00:05:24.450
thank you.

00:05:24.450 --> 00:05:27.420
It's also the first Hollywood
produced studio movie

00:05:27.420 --> 00:05:31.500
in 26 years to feature
an all Asian cast.

00:05:31.500 --> 00:05:33.660
And actually only
the second movie

00:05:33.660 --> 00:05:36.370
to do that in all of
Hollywood's history.

00:05:36.370 --> 00:05:38.962
So it's pretty incredible
what's happening.

00:05:38.962 --> 00:05:41.420
You know, the movie is being
produced by Nina Jacobson, who

00:05:41.420 --> 00:05:43.710
did the Hunger Games movies
which made eight gazillion

00:05:43.710 --> 00:05:45.330
dollars I think.

00:05:45.330 --> 00:05:47.430
And John Chu is
directing and he's

00:05:47.430 --> 00:05:50.980
the amazing director of
movies like the Step Up movies

00:05:50.980 --> 00:05:53.080
and, you know, after
"Crazy Rich Asians"

00:05:53.080 --> 00:05:55.800
he's going to do Lin-Manuel
Miranda's "In the Heights."

00:05:55.800 --> 00:06:00.000
he's the super hot director that
brings such an amazing vision

00:06:00.000 --> 00:06:01.044
to the film.

00:06:01.044 --> 00:06:03.210
So naturally from the moment
the film was announced,

00:06:03.210 --> 00:06:06.180
there was so much excitement
about who is going to be cast.

00:06:06.180 --> 00:06:08.520
We found our two
leading ladies early on.

00:06:08.520 --> 00:06:11.320
Constance Woo was the
star fresh off the boat,

00:06:11.320 --> 00:06:13.350
and is going to play
the American born

00:06:13.350 --> 00:06:15.900
Chinese heroine, Rachel Chu.

00:06:15.900 --> 00:06:19.320
And Michelle Yeoh, the legendary
Bond girl who everyone also

00:06:19.320 --> 00:06:21.630
knows as, you know, from
"Crouching Tiger, Hidden

00:06:21.630 --> 00:06:24.540
Dragon," she is going
to be Eleanor Young who

00:06:24.540 --> 00:06:27.780
is the dragon mother-in-law
from hell that

00:06:27.780 --> 00:06:30.660
wants to make Rachel's
life miserable, basically.

00:06:30.660 --> 00:06:32.980
So finding all the
actresses-- because it

00:06:32.980 --> 00:06:36.120
was a huge cast and all these
beautiful actresses playing

00:06:36.120 --> 00:06:39.090
roles like Astrid, and
Araminta, and Peik Lin.

00:06:39.090 --> 00:06:40.184
That was easy.

00:06:40.184 --> 00:06:42.600
There were so many amazing
actresses from all across Asia,

00:06:42.600 --> 00:06:44.850
from the US, from
England, and we sort of

00:06:44.850 --> 00:06:46.660
have a dream team assembled.

00:06:46.660 --> 00:06:49.320
Gemma Chan, the star of Humans.

00:06:49.320 --> 00:06:52.680
Awkwafina, who's going to be
in the new "Ocean's Eight."

00:06:52.680 --> 00:06:56.640
Sonoya Mizuno, who really
stole the show in "Ex Machina"

00:06:56.640 --> 00:06:57.930
and "La-la Land."

00:06:57.930 --> 00:06:59.790
So that was amazing.

00:06:59.790 --> 00:07:02.550
But when it came
to casting the men,

00:07:02.550 --> 00:07:05.460
especially finding our
leading man, Nicholas Young,

00:07:05.460 --> 00:07:09.030
we had an unbelievably
challenging time.

00:07:09.030 --> 00:07:11.220
There were some wonderful
character actors

00:07:11.220 --> 00:07:12.630
of Asian descent.

00:07:12.630 --> 00:07:15.330
But we suddenly realized that
there are very few actors

00:07:15.330 --> 00:07:18.330
between the ages of
25 and 35 out there

00:07:18.330 --> 00:07:21.420
who can really fulfill that
romantic leading man role.

00:07:21.420 --> 00:07:25.770
You know, who can be the
next Asian Ryan Gosling.

00:07:25.770 --> 00:07:28.080
And finding one who could
do a flawless British accent

00:07:28.080 --> 00:07:29.710
was even tougher.

00:07:29.710 --> 00:07:31.710
So it surprised all
of us that there

00:07:31.710 --> 00:07:33.210
was such a small
pool of people that

00:07:33.210 --> 00:07:35.280
were available and could do it.

00:07:35.280 --> 00:07:37.980
But it really shouldn't
have surprised us.

00:07:37.980 --> 00:07:41.490
John Chu and I really quickly
realized that it's really

00:07:41.490 --> 00:07:43.470
a matter of culture.

00:07:43.470 --> 00:07:45.210
The both of us
grew up in families

00:07:45.210 --> 00:07:48.450
that immigrated from Asia,
so we knew the issues well.

00:07:48.450 --> 00:07:50.520
The simple fact is
that Asian men--

00:07:50.520 --> 00:07:52.530
not just in the US,
but around the world--

00:07:52.530 --> 00:07:54.900
are raised from a
really early age

00:07:54.900 --> 00:07:59.350
to focus on excelling in
the professional realm.

00:07:59.350 --> 00:08:01.960
So to go to the best
schools and work at the most

00:08:01.960 --> 00:08:04.210
prestigious companies.

00:08:04.210 --> 00:08:06.820
So if you're a good looking,
smart, ambitious young Asian

00:08:06.820 --> 00:08:09.400
guy between 25 and
35, you're most

00:08:09.400 --> 00:08:12.100
likely going to be
a doctor, a lawyer,

00:08:12.100 --> 00:08:16.390
or working at Goldman Sachs,
or working here at Google,

00:08:16.390 --> 00:08:17.387
don't you think?

00:08:17.387 --> 00:08:18.970
I mean, I can see
probably some of you

00:08:18.970 --> 00:08:21.690
out here that could
have auditioned.

00:08:21.690 --> 00:08:24.880
And why didn't you, right?

00:08:24.880 --> 00:08:28.450
So that was very
interesting to discover.

00:08:28.450 --> 00:08:34.799
And there is little to no
support for Asian boys growing

00:08:34.799 --> 00:08:40.280
up to ever become actors,
writists, dancers, you know--

00:08:40.280 --> 00:08:40.840
all of that.

00:08:40.840 --> 00:08:42.840
And in fact, I think
telling your Asian parents

00:08:42.840 --> 00:08:44.423
you want to go into
acting is probably

00:08:44.423 --> 00:08:49.350
worse than telling them that
you got your teacher pregnant--

00:08:49.350 --> 00:08:51.570
your gym teacher, you know.

00:08:51.570 --> 00:08:54.270
So this goes back to
my mom and her quest

00:08:54.270 --> 00:08:57.490
for me to work at
someplace like Google.

00:08:57.490 --> 00:08:59.850
Yes, there's a part of her
that's so proud of me that

00:08:59.850 --> 00:09:01.540
I've written a book that's--

00:09:01.540 --> 00:09:03.810
she sees on book
shelves at Barnes Noble.

00:09:03.810 --> 00:09:06.310
Or like gets angry at them when
they don't have it in stock.

00:09:06.310 --> 00:09:10.380
But I truly believe she would
be even happier if I called her

00:09:10.380 --> 00:09:14.520
up and told her tomorrow, hey,
I'm going to go to law school.

00:09:14.520 --> 00:09:16.830
That's just the
plain fact of it.

00:09:16.830 --> 00:09:19.520
So for me, leading a creative
life for the past two decades--

00:09:19.520 --> 00:09:22.130
going to journalism school,
going to art school,

00:09:22.130 --> 00:09:24.350
making experimental films
for weird dance companies

00:09:24.350 --> 00:09:26.390
in New York.

00:09:26.390 --> 00:09:29.960
All that has been a
complete act of rebellion.

00:09:29.960 --> 00:09:32.884
Quiet rebellion, but a
rebellion nonetheless.

00:09:32.884 --> 00:09:35.300
And when we found our leading
man for "Crazy Rich Asians,"

00:09:35.300 --> 00:09:38.870
Henry Golding, who is half
Malaysian and half British

00:09:38.870 --> 00:09:42.440
and who has grown up in Malaysia
and now lives in Singapore,

00:09:42.440 --> 00:09:44.780
I realized we had
so much in common

00:09:44.780 --> 00:09:48.624
because he was also a
rebel in his own way.

00:09:48.624 --> 00:09:49.790
He never went to university.

00:09:49.790 --> 00:09:52.310
He dropped out of
school at age 15

00:09:52.310 --> 00:09:56.360
and went and apprenticed
at a hair salon.

00:09:56.360 --> 00:09:58.440
That was the fun, cool,
creative thing to do.

00:09:58.440 --> 00:10:01.160
And he actually became a
leading hairdresser in London,

00:10:01.160 --> 00:10:03.990
and just last week cut my
hair on the beach in Malaysia.

00:10:03.990 --> 00:10:07.070
So it's really surreal to get
your hair cut by the leading

00:10:07.070 --> 00:10:10.520
man that you've
created in a book,

00:10:10.520 --> 00:10:12.070
and now he's cutting your hair.

00:10:12.070 --> 00:10:13.660
But it was a great haircut.

00:10:13.660 --> 00:10:18.320
Anyway, at age 23,
he left London and he

00:10:18.320 --> 00:10:20.630
was so unbelievably
handsome, everyone

00:10:20.630 --> 00:10:22.963
kept saying you should be an
actor, you should an actor.

00:10:22.963 --> 00:10:24.730
So he moved to Asia
to pursue that.

00:10:24.730 --> 00:10:27.230
And the rest is history.

00:10:27.230 --> 00:10:30.050
And then as I began
meeting all the other cast

00:10:30.050 --> 00:10:32.000
members, all of the actors--

00:10:32.000 --> 00:10:34.980
Ronnie Chang, who is so
amazing in the Daily Show,

00:10:34.980 --> 00:10:39.120
Remi Hii who is from Marco Polo,
Chris Pang, just to name a few.

00:10:39.120 --> 00:10:41.600
I realize we all
shared similar stories

00:10:41.600 --> 00:10:46.072
of this sort of quiet rebellion
in one way or another.

00:10:46.072 --> 00:10:47.780
So I just got back,
as I said, from being

00:10:47.780 --> 00:10:49.670
on the set of "Crazy
Rich Asians" in Malaysia

00:10:49.670 --> 00:10:52.100
and at first I wasn't
planning to go.

00:10:52.100 --> 00:10:54.860
I mean, there was so much
happening with my book being

00:10:54.860 --> 00:10:56.240
launched, everything like that.

00:10:56.240 --> 00:10:58.760
And I didn't want my presence
to really distract the cast

00:10:58.760 --> 00:11:00.830
and distract John.

00:11:00.830 --> 00:11:04.160
But one by one, the actors
started contacting me.

00:11:04.160 --> 00:11:05.840
And I would get
texts from Henry,

00:11:05.840 --> 00:11:06.950
like why aren't you here?

00:11:06.950 --> 00:11:09.260
Like, you have to be here
to see the production.

00:11:09.260 --> 00:11:14.210
And Chris Pang, who is the star
of Netflix series Marco Polo,

00:11:14.210 --> 00:11:19.280
he said, get your ass on a plane
right now and come to Malaysia.

00:11:19.280 --> 00:11:23.250
Something very special is
happening here right now.

00:11:23.250 --> 00:11:24.690
So I did.

00:11:24.690 --> 00:11:28.410
I went to KL two weeks
ago, and arriving

00:11:28.410 --> 00:11:30.550
on the set of the film--

00:11:30.550 --> 00:11:33.120
which was this historic
mansion they found on top of KL

00:11:33.120 --> 00:11:35.880
that they are using to
be Tyersall Park, which

00:11:35.880 --> 00:11:37.740
is the mansion for my books--

00:11:37.740 --> 00:11:40.290
it was one of the most surreal
experiences of my life.

00:11:40.290 --> 00:11:42.180
You know, to sort
of see the sets,

00:11:42.180 --> 00:11:43.810
see these settings
I only wrote about,

00:11:43.810 --> 00:11:47.190
and to meet these characters
that were only in my mind,

00:11:47.190 --> 00:11:49.560
be real and living people.

00:11:49.560 --> 00:11:53.920
It was really amazing
and kind of surreal.

00:11:53.920 --> 00:11:57.150
But the most wonderful thing I
don't think I'll ever forgot,

00:11:57.150 --> 00:12:00.210
was just kind of the
excitement and the look

00:12:00.210 --> 00:12:04.330
of exhilaration in the
eyes of all these actors.

00:12:04.330 --> 00:12:07.820
And I realized-- I mean, I
realized that for most of these

00:12:07.820 --> 00:12:10.070
actors that's assembled here,
the ones especially that

00:12:10.070 --> 00:12:14.420
didn't grow up in Asia, this was
a life changing moment for them

00:12:14.420 --> 00:12:17.690
because for the first time,
these actors and actresses from

00:12:17.690 --> 00:12:19.326
the US, from Canada,
from Australia,

00:12:19.326 --> 00:12:20.450
from all around the world--

00:12:20.450 --> 00:12:21.950
they were getting
to play roles that

00:12:21.950 --> 00:12:25.170
weren't based on stereotypes.

00:12:25.170 --> 00:12:28.220
They weren't playing supporting
roles in white men's movies.

00:12:30.730 --> 00:12:33.370
They weren't Asian mafia
gangsters, or Vietnamese call

00:12:33.370 --> 00:12:35.440
girls, or that
computer geek that

00:12:35.440 --> 00:12:38.810
can hack through the
firewall in three seconds.

00:12:38.810 --> 00:12:40.310
Even if they had
the smallest parts,

00:12:40.310 --> 00:12:42.768
they all felt like they were
being treated like leading men

00:12:42.768 --> 00:12:43.280
or women.

00:12:43.280 --> 00:12:44.889
They each had trailers.

00:12:44.889 --> 00:12:46.930
That had dedicated assistants
and makeup artists.

00:12:46.930 --> 00:12:49.925
And they, for the first time
ever, they all felt like stars.

00:12:52.670 --> 00:12:55.430
Interestingly enough, I
also met some of the actors

00:12:55.430 --> 00:12:57.679
in the film that
came from Asia--

00:12:57.679 --> 00:12:59.720
you know, the ones from
Singapore, Malaysia, Hong

00:12:59.720 --> 00:13:01.520
Kong, China.

00:13:01.520 --> 00:13:03.620
And for them, they were
excited to be in the film,

00:13:03.620 --> 00:13:05.930
but it wasn't that
big a deal for them.

00:13:05.930 --> 00:13:07.280
This was another movie.

00:13:07.280 --> 00:13:10.430
A great movie and part
of, but another movie.

00:13:10.430 --> 00:13:12.187
And one night after
the shoot at wrap,

00:13:12.187 --> 00:13:14.270
a whole group of actors
from all around the world,

00:13:14.270 --> 00:13:16.970
we sat around having drinks.

00:13:16.970 --> 00:13:19.850
And all the actors began
to share their experiences

00:13:19.850 --> 00:13:22.950
of growing up where they were,
whether it was Melbourne,

00:13:22.950 --> 00:13:27.800
Australia or in the middle
of the country in the US,

00:13:27.800 --> 00:13:30.890
and how they had
all come to acting.

00:13:30.890 --> 00:13:33.146
One Asian-American actor
talked about how incredible

00:13:33.146 --> 00:13:34.520
it was for him to
be in this film

00:13:34.520 --> 00:13:38.750
because for once he wasn't the
token Asian guy, and the only

00:13:38.750 --> 00:13:42.592
Asian guy in the whole
cast of white people.

00:13:42.592 --> 00:13:44.300
And he could finally
play a role where he

00:13:44.300 --> 00:13:47.510
was an attractive, desired man.

00:13:47.510 --> 00:13:50.370
And that was huge for him.

00:13:50.370 --> 00:13:53.370
And it was amazing just to
watch the reaction of the Asians

00:13:53.370 --> 00:13:55.020
based in Asia, You the actors.

00:13:55.020 --> 00:13:57.810
Because for them,
it was a revelation.

00:13:57.810 --> 00:14:00.600
These people-- actors like
Pierre Png of Singapore--

00:14:00.600 --> 00:14:02.430
he's the Brad Pitt
of Singapore--

00:14:02.430 --> 00:14:05.385
or Carmen Soo, who is like the
Jennifer Aniston of Malaysia--

00:14:05.385 --> 00:14:06.900
you know, Malaysia's Darling--

00:14:06.900 --> 00:14:09.360
they've only acted in
films with other Asians.

00:14:09.360 --> 00:14:11.980
And they're huge stars
in their own country.

00:14:11.980 --> 00:14:16.500
So for them, they really had
no concept of the challenges

00:14:16.500 --> 00:14:18.570
Asians in other
countries face trying

00:14:18.570 --> 00:14:21.251
to break into the creative arts.

00:14:21.251 --> 00:14:23.750
And a few of them didn't even
know about the whole Hollywood

00:14:23.750 --> 00:14:26.674
whitewashing controversy at all.

00:14:26.674 --> 00:14:28.840
So they were absolutely
floored to discover all this

00:14:28.840 --> 00:14:32.290
and to learn that the movie
has become kind of symbolic

00:14:32.290 --> 00:14:35.240
of a whole other movement.

00:14:35.240 --> 00:14:38.360
So I have to confess, I was like
one of those Singapore actors

00:14:38.360 --> 00:14:40.550
not too long ago myself.

00:14:40.550 --> 00:14:42.320
When I wrote my first
novel, I was simply

00:14:42.320 --> 00:14:45.650
trying to write a funny book
that my friends could enjoy.

00:14:45.650 --> 00:14:50.192
I never imagined it would ever
be published, first of all.

00:14:50.192 --> 00:14:51.900
We have my amazing
agent in the audience,

00:14:51.900 --> 00:14:53.483
Alexandra Machinist
to thank for that.

00:14:56.660 --> 00:14:59.920
I never imagined it would
make any sort of impact.

00:14:59.920 --> 00:15:02.950
And it didn't really
even hit me until I

00:15:02.950 --> 00:15:05.540
was touring for the
first book in Toronto

00:15:05.540 --> 00:15:07.750
and I met a journalist
who was interviewing me,

00:15:07.750 --> 00:15:12.120
and he told me that he
had first found the book

00:15:12.120 --> 00:15:13.630
and was very skeptical of it.

00:15:13.630 --> 00:15:15.300
"Crazy Rich Asians,"
what is this?

00:15:15.300 --> 00:15:18.100
Is this going to be another
book that offends Asians?

00:15:18.100 --> 00:15:19.870
But he decided to read it.

00:15:19.870 --> 00:15:24.040
And he told me he read the book
cover to cover in one night

00:15:24.040 --> 00:15:27.110
and when he was finished,
he started crying.

00:15:27.110 --> 00:15:29.110
And he said, I didn't cry
because of your story.

00:15:29.110 --> 00:15:31.870
I cried because, for the
first time in my life,

00:15:31.870 --> 00:15:34.060
I felt that I had read a
book where I could truly

00:15:34.060 --> 00:15:37.120
identify with the characters.

00:15:37.120 --> 00:15:40.270
I was reading about a guy
that seemed kind of like me,

00:15:40.270 --> 00:15:43.990
who's empowered, who's creative,
who's confident and smart,

00:15:43.990 --> 00:15:46.210
and who doesn't live his
whole life being wrapped up

00:15:46.210 --> 00:15:49.319
in the issue of being Asian.

00:15:49.319 --> 00:15:50.860
So I found a really
interesting quote

00:15:50.860 --> 00:15:54.280
from the playwright,
David Henry Hwang.

00:15:54.280 --> 00:15:56.770
And he was talking about
why the top movie stars

00:15:56.770 --> 00:15:59.920
who are of Asian descent who
make it big in Hollywood,

00:15:59.920 --> 00:16:02.460
they're all native born Asians--

00:16:02.460 --> 00:16:06.370
you know, Jet Li, Jackie
Chan, Chow Yun Fat.

00:16:06.370 --> 00:16:09.520
And he says, why is it that
the most bankable Asians that

00:16:09.520 --> 00:16:12.880
have emerged from this tend
to be foreign born Asians

00:16:12.880 --> 00:16:16.050
as opposed to
American born Asians?

00:16:16.050 --> 00:16:17.550
I think Asians who
grew up in Asia

00:16:17.550 --> 00:16:19.770
aren't wrestling with
identity questions

00:16:19.770 --> 00:16:22.440
as Asians who grew
up in America.

00:16:22.440 --> 00:16:24.730
Since they grew up
not in the minority,

00:16:24.730 --> 00:16:28.650
they had a sense of themselves
that wasn't compromised.

00:16:28.650 --> 00:16:32.190
And that observation for me
was sort of an aha moment.

00:16:32.190 --> 00:16:34.452
I mean, I moved from
Singapore when I was 11

00:16:34.452 --> 00:16:35.910
and I had grown up
in a world where

00:16:35.910 --> 00:16:37.890
I was part of the ruling class.

00:16:37.890 --> 00:16:40.530
So I never realized
how much help that was,

00:16:40.530 --> 00:16:44.730
having that beginning
in Asia that helped me

00:16:44.730 --> 00:16:46.170
when I moved to the US.

00:16:46.170 --> 00:16:48.210
And I think, really, I
would have never dared

00:16:48.210 --> 00:16:53.180
write a book called "Crazy Rich
Asians" if I'd grown up here.

00:16:53.180 --> 00:16:56.630
So I really hope that as
more movies, TV shows, books,

00:16:56.630 --> 00:16:59.270
creative content,
whatever, gets dispersed

00:16:59.270 --> 00:17:03.830
into the world featuring
diverse international casts--

00:17:03.830 --> 00:17:06.349
not just Asians,
but of all races--

00:17:06.349 --> 00:17:10.160
acting alongside Western actors
on an equal playing field,

00:17:10.160 --> 00:17:11.569
new generations
of kids will feel

00:17:11.569 --> 00:17:15.020
empowered to make creative
choices with their lives.

00:17:15.020 --> 00:17:17.960
You know, to rebel, to
become artists, or writers,

00:17:17.960 --> 00:17:19.940
or dancers, or go to
film school, or art

00:17:19.940 --> 00:17:22.790
school, or acting
school, and to be

00:17:22.790 --> 00:17:24.890
able to make their moms proud.

00:17:24.890 --> 00:17:29.660
Even if, like me, they
can't get a job at Google.

00:17:29.660 --> 00:17:30.160
Thank you.

