00:18:47.480 --> 00:18:51.260
widespread popularity
amongst American audiences,

00:18:51.260 --> 00:18:53.690
both Asian and non Asian?

00:18:53.690 --> 00:18:56.240
Were there any conscious
things you considered

00:18:56.240 --> 00:18:58.910
to appeal to a wider
audience while writing,

00:18:58.910 --> 00:19:01.880
or was this just a
happy coincidence?

00:19:01.880 --> 00:19:05.782
P.S., love your
books, smiley face.

00:19:05.782 --> 00:19:06.740
I hope I captured that.

00:19:06.740 --> 00:19:09.735
KEVIN KWAN: I really didn't have
any specific audience in mind

00:19:09.735 --> 00:19:11.360
when I first wrote
"Crazy Rich Asians."

00:19:11.360 --> 00:19:13.970
It was really-- I was writing it
for my friends because I would

00:19:13.970 --> 00:19:14.390
always--

00:19:14.390 --> 00:19:16.790
I would come back from Asia
with all these crazy stories

00:19:16.790 --> 00:19:19.800
about people like that, and they
would be like, write it down.

00:19:19.800 --> 00:19:21.050
Write it down, make it a book.

00:19:21.050 --> 00:19:23.690
And so I really began it as
a collection of short stories

00:19:23.690 --> 00:19:25.490
that I would circulate
to friends of mine

00:19:25.490 --> 00:19:27.980
in New York who
instantly happened

00:19:27.980 --> 00:19:31.010
to be a lot of Europeans and--

00:19:31.010 --> 00:19:34.730
a lot more white people
than Asians, I have to say.

00:19:34.730 --> 00:19:38.660
So it never was meant for
an Asian audience, per se.

00:19:38.660 --> 00:19:42.530
And I just think that what
I found, going to book clubs

00:19:42.530 --> 00:19:45.560
and really meeting fans
from all over the US

00:19:45.560 --> 00:19:47.660
who tend to
predominantly be white--

00:19:47.660 --> 00:19:50.750
you know, I think that's really
80% of my core audience--

00:19:50.750 --> 00:19:52.700
everyone just wants
fresh new stories.

00:19:52.700 --> 00:19:56.420
Everyone wants to be transported
to a new place, a new world

00:19:56.420 --> 00:20:00.770
to discover something new,
and to get lost in a story.

00:20:00.770 --> 00:20:02.030
And this connected.

00:20:02.030 --> 00:20:03.140
This was a new story.

00:20:03.140 --> 00:20:06.340
It wasn't just the same
old boy meets girl--

00:20:06.340 --> 00:20:09.220
not to condemn or in
any way through a shade

00:20:09.220 --> 00:20:12.387
at Nicholas Sparks,
because everyone--

00:20:12.387 --> 00:20:14.720
all his characters are beautiful
blonde people that live

00:20:14.720 --> 00:20:17.822
in North Carolina by the beach.

00:20:17.822 --> 00:20:19.954
People were ready
for something new.

00:20:19.954 --> 00:20:21.120
And that's what they wanted.

00:20:21.120 --> 00:20:23.300
And I think
Asian-Americans actually

00:20:23.300 --> 00:20:26.120
were the second wave that came.

00:20:26.120 --> 00:20:28.580
Because at first I think
there was a lot of hesitance.

00:20:28.580 --> 00:20:29.560
What is this book?

00:20:29.560 --> 00:20:31.410
There was suspicion,
like, is this

00:20:31.410 --> 00:20:33.950
going to portray
us in a bad way?

00:20:33.950 --> 00:20:38.060
But as the word got out, I think
I was embraced by that audience

00:20:38.060 --> 00:20:39.260
too.

00:20:39.260 --> 00:20:41.490
So I'm really thankful for that.

00:20:41.490 --> 00:20:44.310
And in Asia, it was
a hit from day one.

00:20:44.310 --> 00:20:46.980
They were ready for it
because they see this world

00:20:46.980 --> 00:20:47.970
every single day.

00:20:47.970 --> 00:20:50.520
They see the obnoxious
20-year-old couples

00:20:50.520 --> 00:20:53.910
in Rolls Royces, things like
that, and they were like, wow,

00:20:53.910 --> 00:20:55.000
this is fun.

00:20:55.000 --> 00:20:56.460
We get this immediately.

00:20:56.460 --> 00:20:59.420
So it's had this lovely
sort of ripple effect.

