00:23:50.900 --> 00:23:53.360
of wealthy people in Asia now.

00:23:53.360 --> 00:23:56.540
And there are the sort of
Dorothy Wang equivalents, who

00:23:56.540 --> 00:23:57.740
are loving this and love it.

00:23:57.740 --> 00:24:00.900
And they interact as much
on social media themselves.

00:24:00.900 --> 00:24:02.640
But then there's also
another, you know--

00:24:02.640 --> 00:24:05.030
the older money tends to
really kind of look down

00:24:05.030 --> 00:24:05.900
on the new money.

00:24:05.900 --> 00:24:07.550
And so, of course, for
them, they're like OK,

00:24:07.550 --> 00:24:08.360
you want to go do this?

00:24:08.360 --> 00:24:09.170
OK, get kidnapped.

00:24:09.170 --> 00:24:10.350
That's fine.

00:24:10.350 --> 00:24:11.390
Fine by me.

00:24:11.390 --> 00:24:14.690
A lot of the secret--
secrecy is really protective

00:24:14.690 --> 00:24:16.130
because, you know,
these families

00:24:16.130 --> 00:24:20.040
have known the repercussions
of wealth for generations.

00:24:20.040 --> 00:24:21.797
So it's not being
secret for the sake

00:24:21.797 --> 00:24:23.630
of being secretive,
it's secretive because--

00:24:23.630 --> 00:24:26.300
in their past, like,
shit has happened.

00:24:26.300 --> 00:24:29.130
Family members have been
kidnapped or extorted

00:24:29.130 --> 00:24:30.620
and all these
things have happened

00:24:30.620 --> 00:24:32.270
to really force
families to really

00:24:32.270 --> 00:24:34.710
be much more kind of private.

00:24:37.560 --> 00:24:40.630
AUDIENCE: We can keep going.

00:24:40.630 --> 00:24:43.350
JEREMY: How about we
toss it back to our folks

00:24:43.350 --> 00:24:45.420
over in New York City?

00:24:45.420 --> 00:24:48.990
Gloria asks our
next question here.

00:24:48.990 --> 00:24:51.750
What inspired you
to become a writer?

00:24:51.750 --> 00:24:54.690
And what challenges did
you face on your journey?

00:24:54.690 --> 00:24:56.595
And how did you overcome them?

00:24:56.595 --> 00:24:58.870
KEVIN KWAN: Oh, wow,
how long does she have?

00:24:58.870 --> 00:25:01.380
JEREMY: She got four votes,
so it's pretty high up there.

00:25:01.380 --> 00:25:02.900
KEVIN KWAN: OK, cool.

00:25:02.900 --> 00:25:04.050
You know, I always--

00:25:04.050 --> 00:25:06.540
from high school
and on to college,

00:25:06.540 --> 00:25:07.719
I studied creative writing.

00:25:07.719 --> 00:25:09.010
I always wanted to be a writer.

00:25:09.010 --> 00:25:10.468
I felt that that
was the first time

00:25:10.468 --> 00:25:12.450
I could really express
myself creatively

00:25:12.450 --> 00:25:14.490
in any meaningful way.

00:25:14.490 --> 00:25:15.390
So I went to school.

00:25:15.390 --> 00:25:17.880
I got my first degree in
journalism and creative writing

00:25:17.880 --> 00:25:18.960
and I graduated.

00:25:18.960 --> 00:25:21.396
And I couldn't make
a living, basically.

00:25:21.396 --> 00:25:22.770
So I did what
everyone else does.

00:25:22.770 --> 00:25:24.600
I went back to school.

00:25:24.600 --> 00:25:27.760
I went to art school, where it's
even harder to make a living.

00:25:27.760 --> 00:25:31.090
But, you know, I had this
idea that I'm a great writer.

00:25:31.090 --> 00:25:32.520
I'm a great communicator.

00:25:32.520 --> 00:25:34.680
And if I can learn all
these amazing multimedia

00:25:34.680 --> 00:25:38.730
skills like web design and video
design and interactive design,

00:25:38.730 --> 00:25:41.580
and I can bridge those two, I'll
be like this bad ass content

00:25:41.580 --> 00:25:43.560
creator on all ends.

00:25:43.560 --> 00:25:46.440
And that never
happened, of course.

00:25:46.440 --> 00:25:48.120
So I spent 15 years sort of--

00:25:48.120 --> 00:25:52.050
I fell into the consulting world
where I worked for companies

00:25:52.050 --> 00:25:52.770
like TED.com.

00:25:52.770 --> 00:25:55.980
I helped to launch
their website reboot.

00:25:55.980 --> 00:25:58.440
And I would produce these
massive coffee table

00:25:58.440 --> 00:26:03.197
books for Oprah Winfrey, and for
famous architects, and actors,

00:26:03.197 --> 00:26:04.030
and stuff like that.

00:26:04.030 --> 00:26:05.610
So I just kind of
fell into a world

00:26:05.610 --> 00:26:09.750
where I could make money,
literally, and support myself

00:26:09.750 --> 00:26:12.690
in New York, which
was not cheap.

00:26:12.690 --> 00:26:16.740
And then in 2010, my dad died.

00:26:16.740 --> 00:26:18.960
And that was a big wake
up call, because I always

00:26:18.960 --> 00:26:21.624
knew I wanted to write
a book, sort of inspired

00:26:21.624 --> 00:26:22.290
by my childhood.

00:26:22.290 --> 00:26:24.750
And I always thought, I'll
wait till I'm retired.

00:26:24.750 --> 00:26:26.850
I'll do it when I'm 65.

00:26:26.850 --> 00:26:29.970
And losing my dad,
and also talking

00:26:29.970 --> 00:26:32.970
with him about my childhood
and we spent a lot of time

00:26:32.970 --> 00:26:35.280
together in his final
months, it kind of

00:26:35.280 --> 00:26:36.837
refreshed all that for me.

00:26:36.837 --> 00:26:37.920
And I said, you know what?

00:26:37.920 --> 00:26:39.040
This is the time to do it.

00:26:39.040 --> 00:26:40.706
Like, I'm not going
to wait till I'm 65.

00:26:40.706 --> 00:26:42.697
I might not live till I'm 65.

00:26:42.697 --> 00:26:45.030
So I'm going to do it now and
just make it fun, and just

00:26:45.030 --> 00:26:46.140
write it for my friends--

00:26:46.140 --> 00:26:49.860
or for myself, just to
remember these stories.

00:26:49.860 --> 00:26:52.080
And that's kind
of what happened.

00:26:52.080 --> 00:26:54.660
And then Alexandra
got my manuscript.

00:26:54.660 --> 00:26:56.640
I think you were told
to throw it away, right?

00:26:56.640 --> 00:26:58.380
Or to reject it.

00:26:58.380 --> 00:27:00.950
She was told to reject it.

00:27:00.950 --> 00:27:03.100
And she didn't reject it.

00:27:03.100 --> 00:27:05.240
And here we are now.

00:27:05.240 --> 00:27:06.640
Yeah.

00:27:06.640 --> 00:27:07.630
JEREMY: Magic happened.

00:27:07.630 --> 00:27:10.650
KEVIN KWAN: Magic happened.

00:27:10.650 --> 00:27:13.230
JEREMY: All right, who
has got the cash box?

00:27:13.230 --> 00:27:16.360
KEVIN KWAN: You need to
throw it back over there.

00:27:16.360 --> 00:27:19.150
Right behind you.

00:27:19.150 --> 00:27:20.950
AUDIENCE: I kind
of, like you, also

00:27:20.950 --> 00:27:23.310
always wanted to write
a book, but ended up

00:27:23.310 --> 00:27:24.949
studying computer science.

00:27:24.949 --> 00:27:26.490
I actually grew up
in Singapore and--

00:27:26.490 --> 00:27:28.100
KEVIN KWAN: I can tell.

00:27:28.100 --> 00:27:30.470
AUDIENCE: --came to
the US for college.

00:27:30.470 --> 00:27:32.700
But I also took creative
writing classes in college.

00:27:32.700 --> 00:27:35.430
And what they taught to us
was to write what you know.

00:27:35.430 --> 00:27:38.577
But what I knew always seemed
so foreign from what everybody

00:27:38.577 --> 00:27:39.660
else in class was writing.

00:27:39.660 --> 00:27:41.576
And I was like, there's
no way anybody's going

00:27:41.576 --> 00:27:43.620
to be able to relate to this.

00:27:43.620 --> 00:27:44.152
And--

00:27:44.152 --> 00:27:46.110
KEVIN KWAN: That's exactly
what I thought, too.

00:27:46.110 --> 00:27:48.030
That's why I thought
it was unpublishable.

00:27:48.030 --> 00:27:50.410
But I sort of went for it.

00:27:50.410 --> 00:27:51.810
Sorry to interrupt
your question.

00:27:51.810 --> 00:27:52.360
AUDIENCE: OK.

00:27:52.360 --> 00:27:54.230
No, that's inspiring to me,
because when I read your book,

00:27:54.230 --> 00:27:55.590
I was like, this is what I know.

00:27:55.590 --> 00:27:59.590
And I'm-- maybe not particularly
that world, but it's Singapore.

00:27:59.590 --> 00:28:03.290
And it's what I grew up
in, and I've always--

00:28:03.290 --> 00:28:05.622
I was-- I've been
trying to write things

00:28:05.622 --> 00:28:07.080
set in America,
because that's what

00:28:07.080 --> 00:28:10.140
everybody seems to want to read
and to know how to read here.

00:28:10.140 --> 00:28:12.207
But I think your
book has given me

00:28:12.207 --> 00:28:14.040
that insight that maybe
it's possible for me

00:28:14.040 --> 00:28:14.915
to write what I know.

00:28:14.915 --> 00:28:17.986
So maybe it's more of a comment
than a question, so, thank you.

00:28:17.986 --> 00:28:19.610
KEVIN KWAN: I think
it's very possible.

00:28:19.610 --> 00:28:21.420
And I think
publishers out there--

00:28:21.420 --> 00:28:24.060
not just publishers, but
people in film, people in TV--

00:28:24.060 --> 00:28:26.280
they're looking for
fresh ideas that

00:28:26.280 --> 00:28:30.390
aren't just the same stories set
in the same places, especially

00:28:30.390 --> 00:28:31.380
now.

00:28:31.380 --> 00:28:33.885
So I would encourage
you to just go for it.

00:28:33.885 --> 00:28:36.510
AUDIENCE: Is this something you
knew before you started writing

00:28:36.510 --> 00:28:38.340
or is this what you've
learned in your experience?

00:28:38.340 --> 00:28:38.890
KEVIN KWAN: That's what I--

00:28:38.890 --> 00:28:41.070
I mean, that's what
I've learned, really,

00:28:41.070 --> 00:28:44.377
just in my experiences for
the last five, six years.

00:28:44.377 --> 00:28:45.210
AUDIENCE: All right.

00:28:45.210 --> 00:28:46.500
Well, thank you.

00:28:46.500 --> 00:28:47.710
KEVIN KWAN: I think there's
a question back there,

00:28:47.710 --> 00:28:48.720
the guy in the fedora.

00:28:51.269 --> 00:28:52.310
JEREMY: Yeah, good catch.

00:28:52.310 --> 00:28:52.935
AUDIENCE: Hello

00:28:52.935 --> 00:28:53.590
KEVIN KWAN: Hi.

00:28:53.590 --> 00:28:55.430
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:28:55.430 --> 00:28:58.700
Very nervous, sorry, I rarely
talk in front of people.

00:28:58.700 --> 00:29:02.060
But I just wanted to say
that it's really inspiring

00:29:02.060 --> 00:29:06.950
and I'm really grateful to have
you here and experience you

00:29:06.950 --> 00:29:11.210
coming to Google and
giving pretty much

00:29:11.210 --> 00:29:12.690
your life story in short.

00:29:12.690 --> 00:29:15.770
And I-- it's funny
enough, because my wife,

00:29:15.770 --> 00:29:18.350
she's a Asian-American
writer-- or is aspiring--

00:29:18.350 --> 00:29:21.650
and she's pushing out
a novel now, hopefully.

00:29:21.650 --> 00:29:25.781
And she read your book--

00:29:25.781 --> 00:29:30.357
I'm sorry, "Rich People
Problems," "Crazy Rich Asians."

00:29:30.357 --> 00:29:32.690
And she said, about "Crazy
Rich Asians," the same thing,

00:29:32.690 --> 00:29:37.880
that she cried because it
inspired her because she's,

00:29:37.880 --> 00:29:41.330
as an Asian-American
and not a native Asian,

00:29:41.330 --> 00:29:44.000
that she has to deal
with that problem.

00:29:44.000 --> 00:29:46.730
And she struggles
with her image a lot.

00:29:46.730 --> 00:29:50.090
And watching her go through that
process of writing and saying,

00:29:50.090 --> 00:29:53.360
I can't do this, and she's
already like 300 pages in.

00:29:53.360 --> 00:29:55.070
She's like, I don't
know what else to do,

00:29:55.070 --> 00:29:55.986
or what else to write.

00:29:55.986 --> 00:29:56.915
It's-- she struggles.

00:29:56.915 --> 00:29:58.040
KEVIN KWAN: She's doing it.

00:29:58.040 --> 00:29:58.630
AUDIENCE: Yeah, exactly.

00:29:58.630 --> 00:29:59.840
KEVIN KWAN: I can tell
that she's really doing it.

00:29:59.840 --> 00:30:00.360
AUDIENCE: Exactly.

00:30:00.360 --> 00:30:01.193
And I tell her this.

00:30:01.193 --> 00:30:05.620
And I said look, Kevin did it.

00:30:05.620 --> 00:30:08.930
And it's funny because, I
say look, he's doing it.

00:30:08.930 --> 00:30:12.200
And that's all you have to say
to yourself that you can do it

00:30:12.200 --> 00:30:13.550
as well.

00:30:13.550 --> 00:30:15.590
And she said-- she told me to--

00:30:15.590 --> 00:30:17.480
she texted me
saying, oh, my god,

00:30:17.480 --> 00:30:19.992
you need to tell him,
and ask his agent,

00:30:19.992 --> 00:30:22.200
that if she could read my
writing and all this stuff.

00:30:22.200 --> 00:30:24.080
But I just wanted to say--

00:30:24.080 --> 00:30:25.280
AUDIENCE: It's cool.

00:30:25.280 --> 00:30:26.120
AUDIENCE: Thank you Alexandra.

00:30:26.120 --> 00:30:28.286
But I just wanted to say,
from the bottom my heart--

00:30:28.286 --> 00:30:31.940
because it inspired me too.

00:30:31.940 --> 00:30:35.600
Because I actually know John
M Chu as well, because I've

00:30:35.600 --> 00:30:39.920
worked with the LXD, and he
has produced that film series,

00:30:39.920 --> 00:30:42.180
because I'm a aspiring
dancer as well.

00:30:42.180 --> 00:30:46.844
So, small world, but I just
want to say thank you very much.

00:30:46.844 --> 00:30:47.760
KEVIN KWAN: Thank you.

00:30:47.760 --> 00:30:48.593
And I just want to--

00:30:51.380 --> 00:30:54.060
tell your wife, you
know, one page at a time.

00:30:54.060 --> 00:30:55.510
And every day I had self-doubt.

00:30:55.510 --> 00:30:58.300
And everyday I was thinking,
why the hell am I doing this?

00:30:58.300 --> 00:31:03.890
But some thing made me just
keep going until I was done.

00:31:03.890 --> 00:31:05.570
So good luck to her.

00:31:05.570 --> 00:31:07.280
Thanks.

00:31:07.280 --> 00:31:08.530
There's a question back there.

00:31:13.417 --> 00:31:14.250
AUDIENCE: Hi, Kevin.

00:31:14.250 --> 00:31:14.994
KEVIN KWAN: Hi.

00:31:14.994 --> 00:31:16.660
AUDIENCE: I'm so happy
to be here today.

00:31:16.660 --> 00:31:18.394
I'm actually from
The New York office.

00:31:18.394 --> 00:31:19.060
KEVIN KWAN: Yay.

00:31:19.060 --> 00:31:21.390
AUDIENCE: Yeah, really
glad to be in town.

00:31:21.390 --> 00:31:24.240
I had a question for you, and
maybe this is a little deeper

00:31:24.240 --> 00:31:25.120
beyond the movie.

00:31:25.120 --> 00:31:29.850
But I wanted to ask you how
you would address the identity

00:31:29.850 --> 00:31:34.590
crisis between first and
second generation Asians today?

00:31:34.590 --> 00:31:38.040
So I'm kind of a border first
generation, second generation

00:31:38.040 --> 00:31:39.330
Asian.

00:31:39.330 --> 00:31:41.250
I came here when I
was around 2 and 1/2

00:31:41.250 --> 00:31:44.760
and grew up in a very rural
part of South Carolina.

00:31:44.760 --> 00:31:46.200
And now I'm living in the city.

00:31:46.200 --> 00:31:48.810
And I feel like a lot of
the issues in your book,

00:31:48.810 --> 00:31:52.065
I can relate to, but at
the same time I can't--

00:31:52.065 --> 00:31:57.400
I can relate to in a sense where
my removed family on WeChat

00:31:57.400 --> 00:31:59.205
are posting about a
lot of these things

00:31:59.205 --> 00:32:00.330
that they're going through.

00:32:00.330 --> 00:32:02.340
But that I'm living
in a countryside,

00:32:02.340 --> 00:32:06.100
right, growing up and playing
basketball or riding a scooter.

00:32:06.100 --> 00:32:11.220
So how do you address people who
are in this interstitial place

00:32:11.220 --> 00:32:11.820
then?

00:32:11.820 --> 00:32:12.970
How do you bridge that gap?

00:32:12.970 --> 00:32:15.750
KEVIN KWAN: I wish I
had the answer for you

00:32:15.750 --> 00:32:18.390
because I'm trying to
figure it out myself.

00:32:18.390 --> 00:32:21.480
And I think for me,
the creative process

00:32:21.480 --> 00:32:24.810
has been really healing
and really enlightening.

00:32:24.810 --> 00:32:29.340
As I wrote, I was beginning
to understand my family more,

00:32:29.340 --> 00:32:31.909
and situations the
characters would go through

00:32:31.909 --> 00:32:33.450
are a lot of situations
I go through.

00:32:33.450 --> 00:32:35.970
The struggle between
family commitment

00:32:35.970 --> 00:32:38.400
and your own
personal fulfillment,

00:32:38.400 --> 00:32:42.000
that I think is one of the core
issues of the intergenerational

00:32:42.000 --> 00:32:44.370
struggles within the
Asian communities--

00:32:44.370 --> 00:32:46.950
not just in the US,
but in Asia, too.

00:32:46.950 --> 00:32:50.070
I think that's a big thing
that's really happening.

00:32:50.070 --> 00:32:53.332
And we're all
muddling through it.

00:32:53.332 --> 00:32:55.290
And I think you see the
characters in my books,

00:32:55.290 --> 00:32:56.850
too, might have a
billion dollars,

00:32:56.850 --> 00:32:59.160
might be beautiful like
Astrid, but they're still

00:32:59.160 --> 00:33:01.590
dealing with their
mothers and their fathers,

00:33:01.590 --> 00:33:05.700
and the repercussions
of their actions.

00:33:05.700 --> 00:33:09.840
So my formula was
to just be creative.

00:33:09.840 --> 00:33:12.920
And to just really tried to
find voice to my expression,

00:33:12.920 --> 00:33:17.800
and that for me has been really
healing and very enlightening.

00:33:17.800 --> 00:33:19.230
So I hope you find yours

00:33:19.230 --> 00:33:20.396
AUDIENCE: Thank you so much.

00:33:33.720 --> 00:33:35.447
AUDIENCE: Hey, Kevin.

00:33:35.447 --> 00:33:36.780
Been meaning to read your books.

00:33:36.780 --> 00:33:39.840
Haven't yet, but I will now
that I've-- you know, you came.

00:33:39.840 --> 00:33:42.810
Anyway, I realize this is
probably beyond your expertise

00:33:42.810 --> 00:33:44.790
but since you study
human nature and stuff

00:33:44.790 --> 00:33:47.040
I thought I'd ask you anyway.

00:33:47.040 --> 00:33:49.800
I have a one-year-old boy
and another girl on the way.

00:33:49.800 --> 00:33:52.950
I was trying to figure out,
I'm to be raising them here

00:33:52.950 --> 00:33:53.790
in California.

00:33:53.790 --> 00:33:56.340
They're going to be
an ethnic minority.

00:33:56.340 --> 00:33:58.800
I think Asians are 12% of
the state or something, still

00:33:58.800 --> 00:34:01.680
pretty minorityish.

00:34:01.680 --> 00:34:04.920
Do you feel like it's,
overall, more productive

00:34:04.920 --> 00:34:08.750
for children to have their
ethnic identity emphasized

00:34:08.750 --> 00:34:11.489
and be like, this is who you
are, your identity, blah, blah?

00:34:11.489 --> 00:34:14.909
Or more deemphasized,
like, you know,

00:34:14.909 --> 00:34:17.620
just play the cards you're
dealt. Don't worry about it.

00:34:17.620 --> 00:34:19.500
Just do your best, et cetera?

00:34:19.500 --> 00:34:20.610
KEVIN KWAN: Wow.

00:34:20.610 --> 00:34:24.480
I don't feel I can really answer
that with any true expertise.

00:34:24.480 --> 00:34:28.110
I think, first of all, it's
great that you're here in LA,

00:34:28.110 --> 00:34:30.750
because I think we see so
much more diversity here

00:34:30.750 --> 00:34:33.480
than almost anywhere
else in the nation.

00:34:33.480 --> 00:34:35.562
You're not in South
Carolina in a rural town.

00:34:35.562 --> 00:34:37.020
I grew up in a town
where I-- there

00:34:37.020 --> 00:34:40.020
were really three other Asians.

00:34:40.020 --> 00:34:43.800
But I didn't have the sort of
identity issues that they had.

00:34:43.800 --> 00:34:45.179
I realize that now.

00:34:45.179 --> 00:34:46.650
And I realize now
why they hated me

00:34:46.650 --> 00:34:50.370
because I would interact
so freely with everyone,

00:34:50.370 --> 00:34:53.909
whereas they really felt
siloed in this Asian world.

00:34:53.909 --> 00:34:57.300
I think you have to find a
balance where you can raise

00:34:57.300 --> 00:35:01.290
them to be proud of their
identity, and the history,

00:35:01.290 --> 00:35:04.380
and the amazing legacy
of where they come from.

00:35:04.380 --> 00:35:07.420
I don't know if you're
ethnic Chinese or Korean?

00:35:07.420 --> 00:35:09.710
AUDIENCE: I am, but my
wife's Filipino, so--

00:35:09.710 --> 00:35:10.320
ish.

00:35:10.320 --> 00:35:13.000
KEVIN KWAN: I mean,
two amazing cultures.

00:35:13.000 --> 00:35:18.180
So I think if you can balance
that with also integrating them

00:35:18.180 --> 00:35:20.130
into this world, but
also showing them

00:35:20.130 --> 00:35:24.610
how great their ancestry was.

00:35:24.610 --> 00:35:28.470
If you can travel with them back
to Asia or to the Philippines--

00:35:28.470 --> 00:35:31.380
I mean, I think Filipinos
are just so cool--

00:35:31.380 --> 00:35:33.430
one of the coolest
cultures in the world.

00:35:33.430 --> 00:35:37.669
I think that will really help
them bridge the two worlds.

00:35:37.669 --> 00:35:38.460
AUDIENCE: OK, cool.

00:35:38.460 --> 00:35:38.970
Thanks.

00:35:38.970 --> 00:35:39.761
KEVIN KWAN: Thanks.

00:35:43.580 --> 00:35:45.249
JEREMY: Oh, that was close.

00:35:45.249 --> 00:35:46.040
Good throw, though.

00:35:50.600 --> 00:35:53.480
AUDIENCE: So I ask this question
on Dory, but no one voted it,

00:35:53.480 --> 00:35:56.930
so I'll just ask
anyway, on my own.

00:35:56.930 --> 00:35:58.190
Yeah, I read all three books.

00:35:58.190 --> 00:36:00.770
And I feel like they're
really well tied together.

00:36:00.770 --> 00:36:02.450
So I'm just curious,
did you have

00:36:02.450 --> 00:36:05.000
a kind of a vision for a
trilogy when you first started?

00:36:05.000 --> 00:36:06.890
Or did you just write
and go along with it

00:36:06.890 --> 00:36:08.960
and refer back to the
first book when trying

00:36:08.960 --> 00:36:10.250
to tie everything together?

00:36:10.250 --> 00:36:11.060
KEVIN KWAN: I
really had a vision.

00:36:11.060 --> 00:36:12.143
I really wanted to write--

00:36:12.143 --> 00:36:14.150
one, I knew the story
I wanted to tell.

00:36:14.150 --> 00:36:17.750
And I knew would take like
1800 pages to tell it.

00:36:17.750 --> 00:36:20.360
And I knew that that
would never get published.

00:36:20.360 --> 00:36:25.880
And so, I thought trilogy
was the way to go with that.

00:36:25.880 --> 00:36:28.490
And I'm lucky I actually
got to write three books

00:36:28.490 --> 00:36:31.140
and really tell the full story.

00:36:31.140 --> 00:36:33.752
AUDIENCE: Thanks.

00:36:33.752 --> 00:36:35.210
JEREMY: Going off
of that question,

00:36:35.210 --> 00:36:39.280
I just want to ask this
one from the online forum.

00:36:39.280 --> 00:36:43.390
Lauren from New York
asks if you can tell us

00:36:43.390 --> 00:36:46.090
about some crazy rich
Asian experiences

00:36:46.090 --> 00:36:48.500
that you've had like
personally in your own life.

00:36:48.500 --> 00:36:51.140
I know you said that you're
not in the books themselves,

00:36:51.140 --> 00:36:54.580
but how about, like, anything
that maybe didn't make it

00:36:54.580 --> 00:36:59.230
into the book, that didn't
make it into these three books?

00:36:59.230 --> 00:37:01.770
KEVIN KWAN: There's so much.

00:37:01.770 --> 00:37:02.395
Where to begin?

00:37:06.810 --> 00:37:08.730
I'm totally stumped
at the moment

00:37:08.730 --> 00:37:10.870
because, you know-- let's see.

00:37:10.870 --> 00:37:13.340
I've been to crazy weddings,
for example, that were

00:37:13.340 --> 00:37:15.210
even crazier than the books--

00:37:15.210 --> 00:37:17.480
than what I describe
in the books.

00:37:17.480 --> 00:37:19.329
So that's one of them.

00:37:19.329 --> 00:37:20.370
Keep telling the stories.

00:37:24.110 --> 00:37:28.640
Weddings involving three palaces
in Europe, in one wedding,

00:37:28.640 --> 00:37:29.360
things like that.

00:37:29.360 --> 00:37:32.479
And amazing ice
sculptures and little kids

00:37:32.479 --> 00:37:34.770
getting their tongues stuck
licking the ice sculptures,

00:37:34.770 --> 00:37:36.350
and, you know.

00:37:36.350 --> 00:37:39.195
It's just a very interesting
and varied world.

00:37:39.195 --> 00:37:40.070
And it's more about--

00:37:40.070 --> 00:37:42.860
I remember characters,
more, and meeting

00:37:42.860 --> 00:37:45.500
these strange,
interesting characters.

00:37:45.500 --> 00:37:51.150
When I was in Shanghai
there was this person

00:37:51.150 --> 00:37:53.850
that wanted to meet me
because he had read my books.

00:37:53.850 --> 00:37:56.750
And so it was sort of
very covertly set up.

00:37:56.750 --> 00:37:59.810
And he took me to
his private club.

00:37:59.810 --> 00:38:02.300
And he's one of
the seven members

00:38:02.300 --> 00:38:06.260
of this very private club
that only has seven members,

00:38:06.260 --> 00:38:08.360
because it's so exclusive.

00:38:08.360 --> 00:38:12.260
But it was this vast estate
in the middle of Shanghai--

00:38:12.260 --> 00:38:15.230
this amazing huge mansion
with gardens and sculptures

00:38:15.230 --> 00:38:17.900
and water features and
private chefs, just

00:38:17.900 --> 00:38:21.950
to entertain seven
people and their guests.

00:38:21.950 --> 00:38:25.730
So it's mind blowing,
what's happening out there

00:38:25.730 --> 00:38:28.490
that I've been lucky.

00:38:28.490 --> 00:38:30.862
Or unlucky to have witnessed.

00:38:34.560 --> 00:38:38.180
JEREMY: Will go ahead and go
for another Dory question here

00:38:38.180 --> 00:38:40.440
and then we'll wrap up
in just a little bit.

00:38:40.440 --> 00:38:42.860
So if there are any last
questions in the audience,

00:38:42.860 --> 00:38:45.630
definitely tee that up.

00:38:45.630 --> 00:38:50.780
Grace in Mountain View asks,
career tracks in liberal arts

00:38:50.780 --> 00:38:53.720
are generally not very
popular or strongly enforced

00:38:53.720 --> 00:38:56.120
in the Asian culture.

00:38:56.120 --> 00:38:58.760
What kinds of
obstacles and pressures

00:38:58.760 --> 00:39:00.680
did you face as an Asian writer?

00:39:00.680 --> 00:39:04.160
And what did you
learn in the process?

00:39:04.160 --> 00:39:08.090
KEVIN KWAN: You know I
was really lucky because I

00:39:08.090 --> 00:39:11.810
had parents that
were actually very

00:39:11.810 --> 00:39:14.090
open to my doing crazy things.

00:39:14.090 --> 00:39:17.540
As much as my mom wanted me
to be a lawyer or a doctor

00:39:17.540 --> 00:39:21.050
or to work at Google,
she didn't mind

00:39:21.050 --> 00:39:23.720
that I went off and did this
strange thing that she couldn't

00:39:23.720 --> 00:39:27.240
even explain to people, like,
what is a creative consultant?

00:39:27.240 --> 00:39:31.020
You know, I can't even
explain it most of the times.

00:39:31.020 --> 00:39:37.770
But I think that the struggle
really was all internal.

00:39:37.770 --> 00:39:40.980
It's a struggle of self-doubt.

00:39:40.980 --> 00:39:43.130
And as soon as I
began to write it,

00:39:43.130 --> 00:39:47.900
you begin to see inroads as to
how you can make this happen.

00:39:47.900 --> 00:39:52.340
So for me, I very quickly
was able to find an agent who

00:39:52.340 --> 00:39:53.720
wanted to rep the book.

00:39:53.720 --> 00:39:56.570
So I didn't have a struggle
that I think a lot of authors

00:39:56.570 --> 00:39:58.280
go through for years
and years and years.

00:39:58.280 --> 00:40:00.738
I have friends who have been
writing their novels for seven

00:40:00.738 --> 00:40:03.470
years, or have
submitted their novels

00:40:03.470 --> 00:40:09.890
to like 30 agents or publishers
who don't have the same luck.

00:40:09.890 --> 00:40:12.050
And I don't know
what the answer is.

00:40:12.050 --> 00:40:13.730
It's a tough, tough business.

00:40:13.730 --> 00:40:17.000
I think any creative endeavor
is a tough, tough business.

00:40:17.000 --> 00:40:22.010
And you just have to want it bad
enough, and to be persistent,

00:40:22.010 --> 00:40:24.420
I think.

00:40:24.420 --> 00:40:26.114
Did I answer the question?

00:40:26.114 --> 00:40:27.010
JEREMY: I think so.

00:40:27.010 --> 00:40:28.459
Persistency is key.

00:40:28.459 --> 00:40:29.250
That's where I got.

00:40:29.250 --> 00:40:30.770
KEVIN KWAN: Yeah.

00:40:30.770 --> 00:40:32.590
JEREMY: All right.

00:40:32.590 --> 00:40:36.460
Any last cash box questions?

00:40:36.460 --> 00:40:39.412
KEVIN KWAN: I think
there's one more from--

00:40:39.412 --> 00:40:41.120
AUDIENCE: So, so much--
did I turn it on?

00:40:41.120 --> 00:40:41.619
Yeah.

00:40:41.619 --> 00:40:45.050
So, so much of the
book is wonderful food,

00:40:45.050 --> 00:40:48.275
amazing fashion,
beautiful watches, gowns!

00:40:48.275 --> 00:40:50.570
Like, where did you
get all that from?

00:40:50.570 --> 00:40:52.830
Is it from-- obviously
you said real people,

00:40:52.830 --> 00:40:55.690
but did you consult
with fashion designers?

00:40:55.690 --> 00:40:57.652
Like, I would love about
that whole process.

00:40:57.652 --> 00:40:58.610
KEVIN KWAN: Not really.

00:40:58.610 --> 00:41:00.560
I mean, it's like I said,
it's all direct observation,

00:41:00.560 --> 00:41:01.310
number one.

00:41:01.310 --> 00:41:03.260
But as I began to
create the characters,

00:41:03.260 --> 00:41:06.930
you sort of begin to imagine
how they will dress, basically.

00:41:06.930 --> 00:41:10.940
And in the first
book I was really

00:41:10.940 --> 00:41:14.030
trying to satirize this
culture of materialism,

00:41:14.030 --> 00:41:17.299
and money, and people
being label whores,

00:41:17.299 --> 00:41:19.340
because whenever I went
to Asia I would see that.

00:41:19.340 --> 00:41:21.530
I would have people always
ask me, what are you wearing?

00:41:21.530 --> 00:41:22.363
Who made your shoes?

00:41:22.363 --> 00:41:23.480
Let's look at your watch.

00:41:23.480 --> 00:41:26.810
Like, they're so obsessed
with labels, and everything

00:41:26.810 --> 00:41:29.690
that you are wearing,
because people really

00:41:29.690 --> 00:41:31.370
identify with brands there.

00:41:31.370 --> 00:41:34.007
And it really signifies, and
it's so important to them.

00:41:34.007 --> 00:41:35.840
And so I wanted to kind
of make fun of that.

00:41:35.840 --> 00:41:38.048
And I asked my editor, I
was like, what do you think?

00:41:38.048 --> 00:41:40.910
And she was like, I love it, and
the fans are going to love it.

00:41:40.910 --> 00:41:43.760
And she was right, because more
and more-- in the second book,

00:41:43.760 --> 00:41:46.389
I put in less brands
because I thought,

00:41:46.389 --> 00:41:47.930
I'm really getting
to the story and I

00:41:47.930 --> 00:41:50.346
don't have to describe what
everything Ashford is wearing,

00:41:50.346 --> 00:41:51.407
in every scene.

00:41:51.407 --> 00:41:53.240
And then the notes came
back from my editor.

00:41:53.240 --> 00:41:55.760
Please describe everything
she's wearing in every scene,

00:41:55.760 --> 00:41:58.250
like, head to toe--

00:41:58.250 --> 00:41:59.270
and the guys, too.

00:41:59.270 --> 00:42:00.620
Like, the fans want to know.

00:42:00.620 --> 00:42:02.690
The readers love this.

00:42:02.690 --> 00:42:05.280
And so that's what I've done.

00:42:05.280 --> 00:42:06.410
Yeah.

00:42:06.410 --> 00:42:10.020
Interesting story for
you from the movie--

00:42:10.020 --> 00:42:13.860
John Chu is so dedicated to
getting every detail right,

00:42:13.860 --> 00:42:16.940
but there was a moment
in the script where

00:42:16.940 --> 00:42:20.810
a character gives another
character a watch as a present.

00:42:20.810 --> 00:42:24.260
And so he said to me,
like, would this person

00:42:24.260 --> 00:42:26.480
get this watch,
this certain brand?

00:42:26.480 --> 00:42:30.880
And I was like, absolutely not.

00:42:30.880 --> 00:42:33.047
And he's like, so what would
he-- what would he get?

00:42:33.047 --> 00:42:34.796
I was like, well, you
know, this character

00:42:34.796 --> 00:42:36.800
would be given probably
an amazing collectible

00:42:36.800 --> 00:42:42.820
vintage Rolex Paul Newman
Daytona Panda, you know.

00:42:42.820 --> 00:42:44.300
And so we found one.

00:42:44.300 --> 00:42:46.960
Like we sort of went,
connect the dots,

00:42:46.960 --> 00:42:50.980
and an amazing very
generous crazy rich Asian

00:42:50.980 --> 00:42:56.960
lent us his $500,000 Paul
Newman Panda Daytona.

00:42:56.960 --> 00:43:01.040
And it was flown around
the world on set,

00:43:01.040 --> 00:43:05.660
with bodyguards,
in a special box

00:43:05.660 --> 00:43:10.490
for a scene that lasted
literally, I would say,

00:43:10.490 --> 00:43:12.360
quarter of a second.

00:43:12.360 --> 00:43:12.860
Yeah.

00:43:12.860 --> 00:43:17.101
But that's how much we wanted
to get every detail right.

00:43:17.101 --> 00:43:18.850
JEREMY: Is that the
watch you have on now?

00:43:18.850 --> 00:43:19.474
KEVIN KWAN: No.

00:43:21.710 --> 00:43:22.670
I wish.

00:43:22.670 --> 00:43:25.295
But it's funny, the actors were
like, it was your watch, right?

00:43:25.295 --> 00:43:27.020
I was like, no.

00:43:27.020 --> 00:43:28.650
Not even close.

00:43:28.650 --> 00:43:29.400
JEREMY: All right.

00:43:29.400 --> 00:43:32.090
Well, I want to thank Kevin
Kwan for joining us today

00:43:32.090 --> 00:43:33.120
here at Google.

00:43:33.120 --> 00:43:34.430
And thank you.

00:43:34.430 --> 00:43:36.397
Let's go ahead and give
him round of applause.

